#PrudenceMabele Activists launch into "Remember Marikana" chant as Ramaphosa takes to the podium, then they leave auditorium @AfriNewsAgency pic.twitter.com/KmdxYAXFZa JOHANNESBURG – Deputy President Cyril Ramaphosa received a hostile welcome from a group who had come to pay their last respects to AIDS activist Prudence Mabele on Wednesday. They shouted: "Remember Marikana”, disrupting  Ramaphosa’s speech to the extent that he had to be cut short. READ: Community Health Workers boo Ramaphosa on World Aids Day At the time of the Marikana massacre in 2012, Ramaphosa was a non-executive board member of Lonmin and allegedly sent emails to mine management describing the events around the strike as dastardly criminal acts. HIV activist Mabele was laid to rest at Westpark Cemetery in Johannesburg. eNCA